# Merged Cursor Rules: Next.js + TypeScript + Tailwind + Quality + UI/UX + Testing

# Workflow Files (Memory)
Always read and keep these files up to date when relevant:
- `prd.md` for product requirements
- `spec.md` for technical decisions
- `plan.md` for execution tasks
- `status.md` for session updates
If any of these files are missing, create them with a simple template.

# Commit Guidance
Only create commits when a coherent change set is complete (feature finished, bug fixed, or refactor verified).
Do not commit partial work, exploratory changes, or broken tests.
Never commit secrets or local config (e.g., `.env`, credentials).
When asked to commit, ensure tests pass for the touched areas.

# Code Output Format
Do not output code directly in chat. Apply changes by editing files and then cite the changes.

# Repository Context
If a `.cursorrules` file exists in the project root, follow its instructions first.
If there are conflicts between rules, prefer the most recent or most specific instruction.

# Interaction Rules
Avoid unnecessary confirmations or acknowledgements.
Be concise.

# Instruction Priority
System > Developer > Project (.cursorrules) > User

# Code References
When showing existing code, use line-numbered code references that include full file paths.
Use markdown code blocks only for new code not yet in the codebase.
Use a single code block per file when showing edits.

# Testing
If you edit code or tests, run or suggest relevant tests (unit, integration, e2e).
If you cannot run tests, say why.
AI should running test when each Milestones complete.

# Error Handling
If a request is ambiguous, ask for clarification before making changes.
If a rule conflicts with a user request, explain the conflict briefly and propose options.

# Task Completion
Update `status.md` after meaningful work.
Update `plan.md` if tasks or milestones change.
Update `spec.md` if technical decisions change.
Update `prd.md` if scope or goals change.

# Documentation
When adding new rules or workflow docs, keep the README.md structure unchanged unless explicitly asked.

# Safety
Never generate or execute destructive commands unless explicitly requested.
Never fabricate file contents or project details.
Never claim to have run tests if you did not.

# End of Workflow Guidance

# Core Next.js + TypeScript + Tailwind Rules

# Project Overview

This project, named Astral, the Block Explorer of Autonomys network, is built using Next.js and TypeScript. It integrates various libraries for state management, UI components, and data fetching.

# Key URLs

- Astral Block Explorer: https://explorer.autonomys.xyz/
- GitHub Repository: https://github.com/autonomys/astral
- Autonomys: https://autonomys.xyz/
- Academy: https://academy.autonomys.xyz/
- Documentation: https://docs.autonomys.xyz/

# Project Structure

- **Components**: Contains reusable UI components.
- **App**: Next.js app for routing.
- **Hooks**: Custom React hooks for state management.

# Development Guidelines

- Use TypeScript for type safety.
- Follow the coding standards defined in the ESLint configuration.
- Ensure all components are responsive and accessible.
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling, adhering to the defined color palette.

# Important Scripts

- `dev`: Starts the development server.
- `build`: Builds the application for production.

# AI Interaction Guidelines

- When generating code, prioritize TypeScript and React best practices.
- Ensure that any new components are reusable and follow the existing design patterns.
- Minimize the use of AI generated comments, instead use clearly named variables and functions.
- Always validate user inputs and handle errors gracefully.
- Use the existing components and pages as a reference for the new components and pages.

# Lexicon of Terms and Concepts

- **H+AI (Human + Artificial Intelligence)**: The collaboration between humans and AI to enhance capabilities and ensure a harmonious coexistence.
- **Autonomys Network**: A decentralized network designed to provide infrastructure for AI-powered decentralized applications (dApps).
- **deAI Ecosystem**: A stack of components that includes distributed storage, compute, and a dApp/agent layer for building and deploying AI applications.
- **Distributed Storage**: A system ensuring data integrity and availability for AI-related data.
- **Distributed Compute**: Scalable computational resources for AI training and inference.
- **dApp (Decentralized Application)**: Applications that run on a decentralized network, providing enhanced security and transparency.

